        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-12-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-01-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="75" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d75">
                <head>75. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>By October 20, only one finalized bid for development of a nuclear reactor had
                    been received by <gloss target="#t_EURATOM1">EURATOM</gloss>. The U.S. Atomic
                    Energy Commission ordered the suspension of further research and development
                    contracts for the joint U.S.–<gloss target="#t_EURATOM1">EURATOM</gloss>
                    program. On October 23, <gloss target="#t_AEC1">AEC</gloss> Chairman <persName
                        corresp="#p_MCJA1">John McCone</persName> met in Brussels with <gloss
                        target="#t_EURATOM1">EURATOM</gloss> President Etienne Hirsch to discuss the
                    future of U.S.–European cooperation in nuclear energy. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MCJA1">McCone</persName> told Hirsch that continuation of the
                    joint research and development program depended on <gloss target="#t_EURATOM1"
                        >EURATOM</gloss>’s ability to create an adequate nuclear power program.
                    (Memorandum of conversation between <persName corresp="#p_MCJA1"
                        >McCone</persName> and Hirsch, October 23, sent to the Department of State
                    as an enclosure to airgram <gloss target="#t_ECBUS1">Ecbus</gloss> D–92, October
                    29; Department of State, Central Files, 840.1901/10–2959)</p>
            </div>
